","1425–Female":"1425–Deceased","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, England":"Causeway, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Compton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England (but especially in the southwest) named Compton, from Old English <i>cumb</i> ‘short, straight valley’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumpton","meanings":["English (Herefordshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Compton  ."]}]},{"name":"Humphrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Humphry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfrey","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]},{"name":"Humfry","meanings":["From a Norman name, <i>Hunfrid</i>, of Germanic origin, derived from <i>hun</i> ‘bear-cub, warrior’ + <i>fred</i>, <i>frid</i> ‘peace’. The Norman form absorbed the native Old English form, <i>Hunfrith</i>, which existed in England before the Conquest. The spelling with <i>-ph-</i> reflects classicizing influence. Since the 16th century it has enjoyed a modest popularity in England, having been borne most notably by the youngest son of  King Henry IV , the Duke of Gloucester (  1391–1447 ), known as ‘Duke Humphrey’. He was noted as a patron of literature, and founded what became the Bodleian Library at Oxford. In modern times, probably the most famous bearer has been the film star  Humphrey Bogart  (  1899–1957 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Humphrey Compton was born in 1410, in Causeway, Wiltshire, England. He married Isabella. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1410–":"1410–Surnud","1425–Female":"1425–Surnud","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, England":"Causeway, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1410–":"1410–Kuollut","1425–Female":"1425–Kuollut","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, England":"Causeway, Wiltshire, England"},"fr":{"1410–":"1410–Décédé","1425–Female":"1425–Décédée","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Décédé","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, England":"Causeway, Wiltshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Humphrey Compton est né en 1410, à Causeway, Wiltshire, Angleterre. Il a épousé Isabella. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1410–":"1410–Verstorben","1425–Female":"1425–Verstorben","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Verstorben","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, England":"Causeway, Wiltshire, England","lifeSummary":"Humphrey Compton wurde 1410 in Causeway, Wiltshire, England geboren. Er hat Isabella geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"1410–":"1410–Desede","1425–Female":"1425–Desede","1445–1510":"1445–1510","1410–Male":"1410–Desede","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1510":"1510","1410":"1410","Causeway, Wiltshire, En